{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c41770ec-b9e8-42ff-adda-a563835bb262","content":"Collect a **Thread Time (wall-clock) trace** — it captures both on-CPU work and off-CPU waits (locks, I/O, async gaps).\n\n**PerfView command:**\n\n```\nPerfView /ThreadTime /NoGui /AcceptEULA /MaxCollectSec:30 /Zip:True /Merge:True collect\n```\n\nKey flags:\n\n| Flag | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `/ThreadTime` | Enables CPU **and** wait/block context-switch events |\n| `/MaxCollectSec:30` | Limits collection to 30 s (adjust to your repro window) |\n| `/Zip:True /Merge:True` | Produces a single portable `.etl.zip` |\n| `/NoGui` | Headless — safe over RDP |\n\n**Analysis:** Open the resulting `.etl.zip` in PerfView → **Thread Time Stacks** → filter to your process. Stacks with `BLOCKED_TIME` show where threads waited (locks, async I/O, thread-pool starvation). Sort by inclusive time to find the biggest bottleneck.\n\n> **Tip:** If you suspect thread-pool starvation specifically, also add `/ClrEvents:ThreadPool` to capture pool adjustment events.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b9a06cc8-c0e0-4b5f-8d22-5002a2714537","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about performance tracing for an ASP.NET Core .NET 8 app on Windows Server under load. They want to know which trace to collect and what PerfView arguments to use. This is a knowledge question — no tools needed beyond reporting intent.\n\nThey're asking about:\n1. Which trace type captures waits/blocks (Thread Time / Wall Clock profiling)\n2. Specific PerfView command-line arguments\n\nLet me give a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":420,"requestId":"F8C7:14BAB7:532FD0A:5B6150F:69F9FCEE"},"id":"920477ac-ff94-4bc9-9b9c-0ab844a8b51b","timestamp":"2026-05-05T14:21:51.450Z","parentId":"16f9f60e-9dac-412e-bd7b-e7ddc7ba58a2"}
